05335nam a22009735i 9780520936102DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209361027 a10.1525/97805209361022doi  a(DE-B1597)520232  a(OCoLC)52996763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV260.5b.H36 2002eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.5/094932221 aHaney, Lynne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInventing the Needy :bGender and the Politics of Welfare in Hungary /cLynne Haney. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (351 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Conceptualizing the Welfare State -- tPart I. The Welfare Society, 1948–1968 -- tPart II. The Maternalist Welfare State, 1968–1985 -- tPart III. The Liberal Welfare State, 1985–1996 -- tConclusion: Welfare Lessons from East to West -- tMethodological Appendix: Historical Excavation in an Era of Censorship -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInventing the Needy offers a powerful, innovative analysis of welfare policies and practices in Hungary from 1948 to the last decade of the twentieth century. Using a compelling mix of archival, interview, and ethnographic data, Lynne Haney shows that three distinct welfare regimes succeeded one another during that period and that they were based on divergent conceptions of need. The welfare society of 1948-1968 targeted social institutions, the maternalist welfare state of 1968-1985 targeted social groups, and the liberal welfare state of 1985-1996 targeted impoverished individuals. Because they reflected contrasting conceptions of gender and of state-recognized identities, these three regimes resulted in dramatically different lived experiences of welfare.Haney's approach bridges the gaps in scholarship that frequently separate past and present, ideology and reality, and state policies and local practices. A wealth of case histories gleaned from the archives of welfare institutions brings to life the interactions between caseworkers and clients and the ways they changed over time. In one of her most provocative findings, Haney argues that female clients' ability to use the state to protect themselves in everyday life diminished over the fifty-year period. As the welfare system moved away from linking entitlement to clients' social contributions and toward their material deprivation, the welfare system, and those associated with it, became increasingly stigmatized and pathologized. With its focus on shifting inventions of the needy, this broad historical ethnography brings new insights to the study of welfare state theory and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPublic welfarezHungaryxHistory. 0aWomenzHungaryxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a1948.  a1968.  a1985.  aanthropology.  aarchives.  acase histories.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  aeurope.  agender identities.  agender issues.  ahistorical ethnography.  ahungary.  aideological.  aimpoverished peoples.  ainterviews.  aliberal.  amaterialism.  amodern history.  amotherhood.  aneed.  anonfiction.  apolicies in practice.  apolitical perspective.  apolitical science.  apolitical theory.  apoverty.  asocial groups.  asocial institutions.  atextbooks.  awelfare policies.  awelfare society.  awelfare state theory.  awelfare systems.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-20